ond Health, Beyond Choice examines how feminist perspectives can inform public health support for breastfeeding. Written by authors from diverse disciplines, perspectives, and countries, this collection of essays is arranged thematically and considers breastfeeding in relation to public health and health care; work and family; embodiment (specifically breastfeeding in public); economic and ethnic factors; guilt; violence; and commercialization. By examining women’s experiences and bringing feminist insights to bear on a public issue, the editors attempt to reframe the discussion to better inform public health approaches and political action. Doing so can help us recognize the value of breastfeeding for the public’s health and the important productive and reproductive contributions women make to the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh1 aChin, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDodgson, Joan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDowling, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDozier, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuckett, N. Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEden, Aimee R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFentiman, Linda C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoss, Katherine A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiles, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroleau, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall Smith, Paige, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHausman, Bernice L., econtribut